situation is much like #8675 . 
blocking at concurrency.h, line 220:
    ++nwait_consumer_;
    cv_.wait(lock, [this] {    <-------------- HERE -------
        return !priority_queue_.empty() || exit_now_.load();
      });
    --nwait_consumer_;

@cjolivier01 SignalQueuesForKill() blocked! 
 void ConcurrentBlockingQueue<T, type>::SignalForKill() {
  {
    std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock{mutex_};
    exit_now_.store(true);
  }
  cv_.notify_all();  <----------- Waiting here.
}

@cjolivier01 yes, it blocks when exit, not a graceful exit. Happens every time. 
1) When doing multiple test, it blocks at concurrency.h line 220, cv_.wait(lock, .... the test code has already finished the MXPredForward function, blocked at MXPredGetOutput.
2) Cannot have a graceful exit, blocks at notify_all()

Although it shouldn;t be necessary ( https://stackoverflow.com/questions/17101922/do-i-have-to-acquire-lock-before-calling-condition-variable-notify-one/ ), try removing the scope brackets in SignalForKill()
void ConcurrentBlockingQueue<T, type>::SignalForKill() {
  //{
    std::lock_guardstd::mutex lock{mutex_};
    exit_now_.store(true);
  //}
  cv_.notify_all(); <----------- Waiting here.
}
